Project Report: Increase Economic Activity & Quality of Life in the South Stockton Promise Zone¶

By:Shyla C. Solis & Trang Vu¶

1. Objective:¶

There has been outreach from not only public members, but community members , and local representatives to highlight the need for a condition improvement in South Stockton. In order to meet the needs, Stockton city mayor, Michael Tubbs, created a Coalition, “to catalyze the collective impact needed to improve the conditions in the community”. Through an attempt to transform the community, partners from all around the community have joined together to create one vision. As a result, San Joaquin Council of Governments (SJCOG) bacme the Backbone of the Community Vision/Collective Impact Model, Result 8, focused on increasing Economic Activity & Quality of Life. In order to make a difference in these areas, SJCOG needs to know more about the people in the South Stockton Promise Zone (SSPZ).

We will search government websites to go through their data sets to gather nformation specfically to South Stockton. However, if we can not Knowing the number of cost burdened house holds and what predicts it can really help to improve South Stockton. Moving along after finding data, we hope to compare Stockton's results to the overall state statistics as a whole.

We will forecast over 5 years to show what will happen if South Stocktons economic and level ofquality life is not recognized. Using our predictors, we hope will help manipulate the over all metric chosen, which is household burden costs while considering other factors such as health, education, rent, income, population and others.

Linear Regression:¶

6. Response Variable:¶

Our response variable chosen is "Income to Rent Ratio", which in the report is simply titled "Ratio". The response variable represents poverty in the sense that, for as long as people are inside the defined category of, "Burdened", poverty will seep through. Income to rent ratio really effects most other aspects which contribute to poverty. Due to high amounts owners are asking for from renters, it really makes everyones wallets super tight and can cause worrisome to their living state. If all of their money is going to rent, how could families have enough to pay for health care, child care, education, and all other features that matter and contribute to a healthy economic quality way of life. We expect to find a relationship between the income to rent ratio and the number of renters. We expect to find a relationship between ratio and those who did not receive a diploma or equivalent. We also expect to see a relation bewtween those who received a bachdelors degree and the ratio.

10. Project Report¶

Result 8, Increasing Economic Activity and Quality of Life in SSPZ¶

Report by: Shyla C. Solis & Trang Vu¶
South Stockton Promise Zone (SSPZ), in the state of California, has proven to be a huge target area in need of assistance. The people have given numerous surveys to help build an informational system which would in turn help stakeholders decide what needs to be done. The people are faced with a mountain full of issues; issues that continue to increase the poverty levels
One of the top indicators of poverty in the SSPZ, chosen by a vote from the people, housing-cost burden, will be the focus of our research and analysis. Using the available data, we will first get an overall picture of the size of the relevant population. Using educational attainment, we will provide formal knowledge while seeking patterns and relationships within each set. Since the population of interests can be divided into sub areas we will provide information per sub area. 
Diving into descriptions, it is no surprise that the city of Stockton has a high proportion of students dropping out of highschool. The city’s proportion is higher than that of the county and of the nation. When comparing the overall percentages of those who go onto college and receive a bachelor's degree, Stocktons proportion is lower than that of the county and the state. Utilizing the definition from the U.S. Census Bureau, as defined, house-cost burden is when more than 30% of a person's income goes towards rent; we can see what the spread of the population looks like from the state level and the county level. While continuing to explore through visualizations we notice the average category spread throughout Stockton is “High Burden”. This does not mean there are not many people in Stockton who falls under “Extreme” burden, it’s just the median per area of Stockton. 
Since many of the plots needed more data, and Stockton does not have enough data to relay useful information, the next level up used is the data fromSan Joaquin County. The most interesting piece of information obtained using this variable was that of the people who dropped out of highschool, many of them are now falling in the burdened categories with the majority being in “high burden”.
Moving forward, after exploring the factors we would have expected to find a relationship between income to rent ratio and factors such as the number of renters based on zip code, or the number of people with no car or even only one car, however this was not the case. When exploring all possible relationships at once the best we felt was worth exploring were not the best of the best.  
With what we had, we decided to dig deeper into exploring rent to income ratios with the number of occupied housing units being rented. This model could only explain 19% of the variance of the data. Afterwards, we explored the relationship between the ratios and the population of people who received a diploma within a certain age group (18-25yrs). This fator explained even less, only 12% of the variance of the data. The one’s which had more of a chance of having a relationship was the population factors, however, exploring these factors would lean towards greater challenges when deciding what to do if these are meaningful relationships. The best this factor could do came out to only 31%; still no good. 
When switching over to consider multiple factors at one time to relate more to how life really works, we get insight into an interesting model. Using the variables, “Population”, “Total.Num.of.People.Less.Than.Highschool”, and “Total.Num.Diploma.Received” we found a model that accounts for at least 97.9% of the variance of the data to predict “Income to Rent Ratio”. Since these variables are showing importance, these are the factors which should be paid high attention to. 
Although not many useful models were found, one good model may be the start of a good lead. SJCOG, result 8, should look for ways to manipulate the three variables whose presence in the model found so that Income to Rent Ratio can improve. Most times, building partners who have ties to programs for families to help them in the areas which strictly affect the variables chosen are action takers and really help to improve. If the number of diplomas received can increase this will greatly help those who fall into the burdened category move out of that category. 
All while creating new relationships and adding new partners to the table, it will be important to continue monitoring the progress. Each implementation should be tracked and recorded to be able to update any statistical charts to showcase improvements. Also, in order to see which of the three variables predicts the ratio the most there are further tests which can be taken using a different program. If you hire us we can dig even deeper and let you know how to prioritize.
